<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-285-963  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 285 963.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Dec 1989 v62 n12 p57(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A 'bad boy' image? (Toshiba's selling of restricted technologiesto Eastern bloc countries)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Toshiba Corp sold the Soviet Union machinery for manufacturinglow-turbulence nuclear submarine propeller blades in 1987 inviolation of Japanese laws implementing the internationalCoordinating Committee on Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom)agreement.andP;  The firm is also believed to be selling East Germany1M-bit dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) technology in violationof Cocom, though the company denies it.andP;  Toshiba has developed agood set of regulations for complying with Cocom, but some USobservers do not believe the firm is sticking to the rules.andO;Carnegie Endowment Sr Associate Clyde Prestowitz believes that acollision in economic values almost guarantees trade frictionbetween the US and Japan.andP;  Specifically, 'Japan is run for theproducers' while in the US the 'main purpose of the economy is tobenefit the consumer.'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Toshiba Corp. (export-import trade).andO;Topic:     Political IssuesExportEthicsManufacturersJapanInternational LawInternational tradeSemiconductor industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>